            @*<h2 class="blog-post-title">Steps</h2>*@

            <h3>Download Git Tools</h3>
            <p>
                Visit <a target="_blank" href="https://git-scm.com/downloads">git-scm.com/downloads</a> to download Git Tools.<br />
                The installer includes <b>Git Bash</b>, a program where we can type commands for git to execute.<br />
            </p>
            <p>
                For example, I'm on a computer running Windows,<br />
                so I would click the green <b>Download 2.22.0 for Windows</b> button.
            </p>

            <img class="article-image gray-border" width="650" src="~/Images/git-tools-download-thumb.PNG" />

            <p>
                If you are on a Mac or Linux computer, select the download for your operating system.<br />
                Run the Installer that downloads, and simply keep clicking <b>Next</b> to select all of the default options.
            </p>

            <p>
                Once installation is complete, you should be able to <b>Right Click</b> in any folder on your computer<br />
                and see a <b>Git Bash Here</b> option.
            </p>
            <img class="article-image" width="300" src="~/Images/git-bash-here.png" />

            <p>
                Click on <b>Git Bash Here</b> and you will be presented with the Git Bash Prompt:
            </p>
            <img class="article-image" width="650" src="~/Images/git-bash.png" />
            <p>
                Congratulations! You are now set up and ready to run git commands on your local computer.
            </p>
            <hr />

            <h3>Notes</h3>
            <p>
                I usually keep my repositories in a folder at <b>C:/dev</b>.<br />
                This helps when I end up hand-typing URLs, they are nice and short.<br />
                You can keep your projects/repos where you'd like.<br />
                You can even use Git to move projects to other servers.
            </p>
